(20320, 560, 'accordion_section_1_accordion_content', ' Is dead plant material or litter from previous years absent?\r\n\r\n Is the buffer strip between the riparian zone and cultivated lands narrow (less than 10 meters)?\r\n\r\n Is plant vigour poor?\r\n\r\n Has grazing removed almost all of the palatable vegetation?\r\n\r\n Are desirable plants being replaced by unpalatable or undesirable types?\r\n\r\nIs woody vegetation present and maintaining itself? Preferred trees and shrubs are established and regenerating (see list of appropriate trees and shrubs)\r\n\r\n Are noxious weeds present?\r\n\r\nWeeds and grasses have shallower roots than woody species, and are therefore not as capable of controlling erosion. Are there disturbed ground species present such as queen Annes Lace, colts foot, plantain ?\r\n\r\n Are wetland species being replaced by drought tolerant upland species?\r\n\r\n Do palatable trees and shrubs appear to be heavily browsed by livestock?\r\n\r\n Are all the trees old and/or of poor health (as opposed to being various sizes and ages)?\r\n\r\n Do stands of trees have an open, park-like appearance?\r\n\r\nIt is good to have a diversity of species, including shrub species. Grasses are not as adept at maintaining bank structure and increases the riparian areas risk to erosion\r\n\r\n Have trees and shrubs been eliminated from sites (where they should be present)?'),
