(184, 1, '2014-06-10 17:32:14', '2014-06-10 17:32:14', 'Riparian areas are located between the low and high-water marks of watercourses and wetlands, as well as the adjacent lands whose vegetation and soils contain higher concentrations of water than are found in upland areas. Riparian areas are often a unique and biologically rich habitat because they possess a variety of physical, biological and chemical conditions not found elsewhere. In addition to increasing and supporting biodiversity/wildlife habitat (in fact, some plant and animal species can survive only in riparian habitats), these areas are extremely important for humans as well:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Improved water quality</strong> for recreational purposes, drinking water in wells and for livestock</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Water absorption and storage</strong> maintains groundwater levels (for wells), and reduces flooding</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Flood control</strong>plants on the banks reduce the speed of moving water during storm events, reducing the impact of flooding</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Protecting streambanks</strong>prevents eroded soil from entering water</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Shade</strong>helps to reduce water temperature, and increase habitat for species such as salmon, which are of interest to anglers</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Carbon sequestration</strong>plants act as a carbon sink and store carbon from greenhouse gases</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Shelterbelt</strong>shrubs and trees act as a windbreak, reducing wind damage</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Riparian Areas', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'riparian-area', '', '', '2014-07-14 17:10:36', '2014-07-14 17:10:36', '', 2, 'http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/?page_id=184', 0, 'page', '', 0),
