(258, 1, '2014-06-17 13:57:30', '2014-06-17 13:57:30', '<i><b>Planting Vegetated Buffers/Grassy Headlands</b></i>\r\n\r\nTo prevent erosion and promote water filtration vegetation should be present along riparian areas. In some places it may not be possible to keep woody vegetation such as trees or bushes, for example the borders of field crops adjacent to waterways. Grassy strips or headlands are intended for filtration and a setback is an area of land that is left untouched. Together these areas are called Vegetated Buffers. A setback can be incorporated into the vegetated buffer.\r\n\r\nKeeping soil covered by some grass will have multiple benefits for both biodiversity and the farm. Grass will help to reduce erosion as the root mass help to maintain the soil. Helping soil biodiversity will help to improve soil quality through the preservation of soil nutrients and soil structure. Grasses will also act as a filter, helping to reduce the amount of loose soil or suspended inputs such as pesticides or fertilizers washed into neighbouring waterways.\r\n\r\n<b>Grassy strips</b> or headlands are intended for filtration and a <b>setback</b> is an area of land that is left untouched. Together these areas form Vegetated Buffers. A setback can be incorporated into the vegetated buffer. For more information about both setbacks and grassy strips can be found below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Setbacks & Buffers', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '240-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-17 13:57:30', '2014-06-17 13:57:30', '', 240, 'http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/?p=258', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(259, 1, '2014-06-17 13:58:04', '2014-06-17 13:58:04', 'Grass should be present along crop edges, especially those bordering riparian areas along watercourses. These grassy strips can provide habitat for beneficial animals such as predatory spiders and beetles as well as snakes that should feed on some of the bugs affecting crop production. In addition many of these areas are turn around areas for field machinery.\r\n\r\nThese grasses will act as a filter for crop run-off. For the maximum amount filtration to occur, the plants should be dense and established<strong>15 to 20cm (6-8 inches) sod-forming vegetation that uniformly covers at least 90% of an area.</strong> Grass species can be sown, but you can also allow the plants to establish themselves. However, there may be a risk of weed influx.\r\n\r\nThe width of combined riparian edge and grassy strip (vegetated buffer) should be measured from the crop to the edge of the bank . Buffers should be a <strong>minimum</strong> of <strong>10 meters</strong> in width for water filtration to occur. However this width is dependent on the crop (potatoes for example require a larger width compared to less intensive crops such as hay as well as how steep the land issteeper land requires coverage wider buffer as the slopes increase the overland runoff during rainstorms.', 'Grassy Headlands', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'grassy-strips-buffers', '', '', '2014-07-10 20:40:09', '2014-07-10 20:40:09', '', 240, 'http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/?page_id=259', 0, 'page', '', 0),
