(506, 4, '2014-07-10 20:33:06', '2014-07-10 20:33:06', '<img class="aligncenter wp-image-497 size-full" src="http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/riparing-buffer.png" alt="riparing buffer" width="1446" height="770" />\r\n\r\nTo prevent erosion and promote water filtration vegetation should be present along riparian areas. Ideally, deep rooted woody plants like trees and shrubs help to lock the soils and reduce erosion. In some places such as floodplains, trees and shrubs are unable to grow. In these areas try to maintain the herbaceous or non-woody vegetation to reduce erosion. To provide an effective filter it is important to maintain a riparian edge, or vegetated setback, of native species along all waterways and around wetlands.\r\n\r\nDepending on your goals, the amount of space dedicated to a setback will vary. The wider the setback, the more benefits are provided to both the riparian and aquatic ecosystems. The width will be dependent on your own personal goals; are you interested in improving habitat? Reducing sediment or nutrients in run-off? Improving bank stability?\r\n\r\nThe following table provides a list of the benefits that result from different buffer widths.\r\n<table style="height: 220px;" width="447">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266"><strong>Function</strong></td>\r\n<td width="168"><strong>Width</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Bank Stability</td>\r\n<td width="168">5+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Sediment Removal</td>\r\n<td width="168">10+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Soil-Bound Nutrients</td>\r\n<td width="168">10+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Soluble Nutrients</td>\r\n<td width="168">15+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Aquatic Habitat</td>\r\n<td width="168">15+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Terrestrial wildlife habitat</td>\r\n<td width="168">10+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Setbacks & Buffers', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '240-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 20:33:06', '2014-07-10 20:33:06', '', 240, 'http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/?p=506', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(507, 4, '2014-07-10 20:35:10', '2014-07-10 20:35:10', 'Grass should be present along crop edges, especially those bordering riparian areas along watercourses. These grassy strips can provide habitat for beneficial animals such as predatory spiders and beetles as well as snakes that should feed on some of the bugs affecting crop production. In addition many of these areas are turn around areas for field machinery.\r\n\r\nThese grasses will act as a filter for crop run-off. For the maximum amount filtration to occur, the plants should be dense and established<strong>15 to 20cm (6-8 inches) sod-forming vegetation that uniformly covers at least 90% of an area.</strong> Grass species can be sown, but you can also allow the plants to establish themselves. However, there may be a risk of weed influx.\r\n\r\nThe width of combined riparian edge and grassy strip (vegetated buffer) should be measured from the crop to the edge of the bank . Buffers should be a <strong>minimum</strong> of <strong>10 meters</strong> in width for water filtration to occur. However this width is dependent on the crop (potatoes for example require a larger width compared to less intensive crops such as hay as well as how steep the land issteeper land requires coverage wider buffer as the slopes increase the overland runoff during rainstorms.', 'Grassy Strips & Buffers', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '259-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-07-10 20:35:10', '2014-07-10 20:35:10', '', 259, 'http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/?p=507', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
