(544, 4, '2014-07-11 17:41:16', '2014-07-11 17:41:16', 'Riparian areas are located between the low and high-water marks of watercourses and wetlands, as well as the adjacent lands whose vegetation and soils contain higher concentrations of water than are found in upland areas. Riparian areas are often a unique and biologically rich habitat because they possess a variety of physical, biological and chemical conditions not found elsewhere. In addition to increasing and supporting biodiversity/wildlife habitat (in fact, some plant and animal species can survive only in riparian habitats), these areas are extremely important for humans as well:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Improved water quality</strong> for recreational purposes, drinking water in wells and for livestock</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Water absorption and storage</strong> maintains groundwater levels (for wells), and reduces flooding</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Flood control</strong>plants on the banks reduce the speed of moving water during storm events, reducing the impact of flooding</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Protecting streambanks</strong>prevents eroded soil from entering water</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Shade</strong>helps to reduce water temperature, and increase habitat for species such as salmon, which are of interest to anglers</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Carbon sequestration</strong>plants act as a carbon sink and store carbon from greenhouse gases</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Shelterbelt</strong>shrubs and trees act as a windbreak, reducing wind damage</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Riparian Areas', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '184-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-11 17:41:16', '2014-07-11 17:41:16', '', 184, 'http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/?p=544', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(545, 4, '2014-07-11 17:41:56', '2014-07-11 17:41:56', 'Riparian areas are located between the low and high-water marks of watercourses and wetlands, as well as the adjacent lands whose vegetation and soils contain higher concentrations of water than are found in upland areas. Riparian areas are often a unique and biologically rich habitat because they possess a variety of physical, biological and chemical conditions not found elsewhere. In addition to increasing and supporting biodiversity/wildlife habitat (in fact, some plant and animal species can survive only in riparian habitats), these areas are extremely important for humans as well:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Improved water quality</strong> for recreational purposes, drinking water in wells and for livestock</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Water absorption and storage</strong> maintains groundwater levels (for wells), and reduces flooding</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Flood control</strong>plants on the banks reduce the speed of moving water during storm events, reducing the impact of flooding</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Protecting streambanks</strong>prevents eroded soil from entering water</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Shade</strong>helps to reduce water temperature, and increase habitat for species such as salmon, which are of interest to anglers</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Carbon sequestration</strong>plants act as a carbon sink and store carbon from greenhouse gases</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Shelterbelt</strong>shrubs and trees act as a windbreak, reducing wind damage</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Riparian Areas', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '184-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-11 17:41:56', '2014-07-11 17:41:56', '', 184, 'http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/?p=545', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(546, 4, '2014-07-11 17:42:36', '2014-07-11 17:42:36', '<img class="aligncenter wp-image-497 size-full" src="http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/riparing-buffer.png" alt="riparing buffer" width="1446" height="770" />\r\n\r\nTo prevent erosion and promote water filtration vegetation should be present along riparian areas. Ideally, deep rooted woody plants like trees and shrubs help to lock the soils and reduce erosion. In some places such as floodplains, trees and shrubs are unable to grow. In these areas try to maintain the herbaceous or non-woody vegetation to reduce erosion. To provide an effective filter it is important to maintain a riparian edge, or vegetated setback, of native species along all waterways and around wetlands.\r\n\r\nDepending on your goals, the amount of space dedicated to a setback will vary. The wider the setback, the more benefits are provided to both the riparian and aquatic ecosystems. The width will be dependent on your own personal goals; are you interested in improving habitat? Reducing sediment or nutrients in run-off? Improving bank stability?\r\n\r\nThe following table provides a list of the benefits that result from different buffer widths.\r\n<table style="height: 217px;" width="308">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266"><strong>Function</strong></td>\r\n<td width="168"><strong>Width</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Bank Stability</td>\r\n<td width="168">5+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Sediment Removal</td>\r\n<td width="168">10+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Soil-Bound Nutrients</td>\r\n<td width="168">10+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Soluble Nutrients</td>\r\n<td width="168">15+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Aquatic Habitat</td>\r\n<td width="168">15+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="266">Terrestrial wildlife habitat</td>\r\n<td width="168">10+ meters</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\nThere are different things that you can do to maintain the health of your riparian areas. Click on the menu below for more information regarding practices, information and relevant legislation.\r\n&nbsp;', 'Setbacks & Buffers', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '240-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-11 17:42:36', '2014-07-11 17:42:36', '', 240, 'http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/?p=546', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(547, 4, '2014-07-11 17:59:40', '2014-07-11 17:59:40', '<i><b>Reducing or limiting access to riparian areas from livestock</b></i>\r\n\r\nLivestock trample riparian areas, this reduces the function of riparian vegetation resulting in increased susceptibility to erosion and flooding, and reduced water quality. Furthermore, the feces and urine from livestock will have a direct impact on water quality.\r\n\r\nThere are different ways that you can limit the number of livestock that enter your watercourses. Depending on what your goals are (simply improving water quality, or improving water quality and terrestrial habitat) the way that these different activities are carried out may vary.', 'Limiting Livestock Access to Waterways ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '250-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-11 17:59:40', '2014-07-11 17:59:40', '', 250, 'http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/?p=547', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(548, 4, '2014-07-14 16:17:32', '2014-07-14 16:17:32', 'Livestock trample riparian areas, this reduces the function of riparian vegetation resulting in increased susceptibility to erosion and flooding, and reduced water quality. Furthermore, the feces and urine from livestock will have a direct impact on water quality.\n\nThere are different ways that you can limit the number of livestock that enter your watercourses. Depending on your management goals, and the physical characteristics of your pasture, different practices will be appropriate. Excluding livestock from watercourses altogether will improve water quality, but alternative water sources are not always possible. More information about best management practices can be found below.\n\nIt should be noted, however, that <strong>ANY</strong> alteration to a stream or watercourse, <strong>including bridges</strong>, and<strong> limited access ramps</strong>, does require permission through the navigable waters act (1985). A permit is not required for fencing. More information, as well as the appropriate paperwork, can be found here', 'Limiting Livestock Access to Waterways ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '250-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-07-14 16:17:32', '2014-07-14 16:17:32', '', 250, 'http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/?p=548', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(549, 4, '2014-07-11 18:17:43', '2014-07-11 18:17:43', 'Livestock trample riparian areas, this reduces the function of riparian vegetation resulting in increased susceptibility to erosion and flooding, and reduced water quality. Furthermore, the feces and urine from livestock will have a direct impact on water quality.\r\n\r\nThere are different ways that you can limit the number of livestock that enter your watercourses. Depending on your management goals, and the physical characteristics of your pasture, different practices will be appropriate. Excluding livestock from watercourses altogether will improve water quality, but alternative water sources are not always possible. More information about best management practices can be found below.\r\n\r\nIt should be noted, however, that <strong>ANY</strong> alteration to a stream or watercourse, <strong>including bridges</strong>, and<strong> limited access ramps</strong>, does require permission through the navigable waters act (1985). A permit is not required for fencing. More information, as well as the appropriate paperwork, can be found here: <a href="https://www.novascotia.ca/snsmr/paal/nse/paal181.asp">https://www.novascotia.ca/snsmr/paal/nse/paal181.asp</a>', 'Limiting Livestock Access to Waterways ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '250-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-11 18:17:43', '2014-07-11 18:17:43', '', 250, 'http://projects.cs.dal.ca/farming/project/?p=549', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
